## The `async` Keyword

There is a massive catch. If you want to use the magical `await` keyword inside a function, you MUST label that function as `async`.

```dart
// Add 'async' right before the curly braces!
void loadProfile() async {
  print('Starting download...');
  String name = await fetchName(); // Now this is totally legal!
  print('Finished! Name is $name');
}
```
`async` is the warning label that tells Dart: *"Hey, this function contains code that bends time!"*

## Becoming the Box

The moment you label a function `async`, that function immediately turns into a `Future` itself!

```dart
// This function takes 3 seconds, so it MUST return a Future<int>
Future<int> getScore() async {
  int score = await downloadScore();
  return score;
}
```
Now, anyone who tries to call `getScore()` will have to `await` it too! Asynchrony spreads up the chain.

